Project: PCA and tSNE¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on PCA and tSNE. In this project. We will be using the auto-mpg dataset.

Objective:¶

The objective of this problem is to explore the data and reduce the number of features by using dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA and TSNE and generate meaningful insights.

Dataset:¶

There are 8 variables in the data:

  • mpg: miles per gallon
  • cyl: number of cylinders
  • disp: engine displacement (cu. inches) or engine size
  • hp: horsepower
  • wt: vehicle weight (lbs.)
  • acc: time taken to accelerate from O to 60 mph (sec.)
  • yr: model year
  • car name: car model name

  • Most cars are from the years 70,77 and 82

Checking correlation¶

In [13]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot=True)
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • The variable mpg has strong negative correlation with cylinders, displacement, horsepower, and weight - Cars built for sports performance are fuel inefficient and this relationship aligns with that logic
  • horsepower and acceleration are negatively correlated, acceleration is number of seconds to go from 0-60 mph, hence this makes sense i.e. more powerful car will take less time to reach that speed
  • Weight has strong positive correlation with horsepower, displacement and cylinders
  • model year is positively correlated with mpg which may point at gradual improvement in fuel efficiency of cars

  • Group 3 (darkest hue)

In [22]:
# find the least number of components that can explain more than 90% variance
sum = 0
for ix, i in enumerate(exp_var):
  sum = sum + i
  if(sum>0.90):
    print("Number of PCs that explain at least 90% variance: ", ix+1)
    break

Number of PCs that explain at least 90% variance:  3

Observations:¶

  • The original list of 7 features have been cut down to 3 explaining 95% of variance
  • The above translates to 57% reduction in features and 5% loss of variance

# Let's assign points to 3 different groups
def grouping(x):
    first_component = x['Component 1']
    second_component = x['Component 2']
    if (first_component> 0) and (second_component >0): 
        return 'group_1'
    if (first_component >-20 ) and (first_component < 5):
        return 'group_2'
    else: 
        return 'group_3'
In [63]:
data_tsne['groups'] = data_tsne.apply(grouping,axis=1)
In [64]:
sns.scatterplot(x=data_tsne.iloc[:,0],y=data_tsne.iloc[:,1],hue=data_tsne.iloc[:,2])

  • Group 2 has cars that are lower mpg than group 1, have better performance or power features and are from the middle of the model year spectrum
  • Group 3 are the performance cars with low mpg, high horsepower/weight/displacement, highest cylinders and minimum time to accelerate to 60 mph and belong to the older model years
